properties.Asset_Name: North Adelaide - North Adelaide Library and Community Centre - NW
properties.Additional_Info: The Institute building is a historic public building. It is further remarkable that it has retained uses closely related to its original purposes from 1884 to the present day. The Institute has played a continuous role in its social and intellectual life. Although covered by two separate land titles (including the post office), the whole building is listed as one place on the SA State Heritage Register, correctly recongnising the architectural and historical values. The building was designed in the Victorian Free Classical style by then Government Architect E. J. Woods, and its brick and decorated stucco frontage plays an important role in the streetscape of Tynte Street. Any future development of the property should respect its surviving historical and architectural significance and not interpose on the buildings?? historic setting and context. There is scope for redevelopment of the site to the rear and the eastern side of the Post Office, and considerable scope for change inside the buildings, but the original form of the Institute Hall should be recovered in any future adaptive reuse. The North Adelaide Post Office and Institute building is within the Adelaide Parklands and City Layout on the National Heritage list, ID 105758; it is also within the North Adelaide Conservation Area in the Register of the National Estate (RNE,) ID 6434. The North Adelaide Post Office and Institute are included in the State Heritage Register, File reference number 13504

It is a two story facility with a base building constructed by Hindmarsh Construction. It was originally part of the Council??s old Sturt Street Depot, a two storey warehouse built for the City Engineer??s Department in 1939. Council??s last use of the building was in 2012 for archives storage.
